{"name": "Music Composition", "id": 255, "content": "<h2>Harmony</h2>\n\n<p>Reference: Practical Guide To Harmony</p>\n\n<p>Chords: Multiple tones sounding together.</p>\n\n<p><strong>Consonant Chords: Triads </strong></p>\n\n<p>Triad: 3 tones separated from each other by interval of a <strong>Third</strong>.</p>\n\n<p><strong>Triads of a Major Scale:</strong></p>\n\n<p>Tonic Triad - on 1st degree of scale</p>\n\n<p>Subdominant Triad - on 3rd</p>\n\n<p>Dominant Triad - on 5th</p>\n\n<p>These 3 combined contain all the diatonic degrees of the scale, sound good together, are sufficient for harmonization of any melody that does not surpass the key in question.</p>\n\n<p>Subdominant Triad,&nbsp;Dominant Triad are also <strong><em>tonic</em></strong>&nbsp; in those keys which are nearest to the given key in Circle Of Fifths.</p>\n\n<p>&nbsp;</p>\n", "authorId": 1, "subject": "hidden", "tags": [], "img": "", "summary": "string", "lastUpdated": "2022-04-04 19:48:51.253027"}